===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|shap|lang=enm}}, {{term|schape|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|gesceap|ġesceap|shape, form, created being, creature, creation, dispensation, fate, condition, sex, gender, genitalia|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|ga-|lang=gem-pro}} + {{recons|skapą||shape, nature, condition|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|(s)kÀp-||to split, cut|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with {{etyl|dum|-}} {{term|schap||form|lang=dum}}, {{etyl|gmh|-}} {{term|geschaf||creature|lang=gmh}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|skap||state, condition, temper, mood|lang=is}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# The [[status]] or [[condition]] of something
#: ''The used bookshop wouldn't offer much due to the poor '''shape''' of the book.''
# [[condition|Condition]] of personal [[health]], especially muscular health.
#: ''The vet checked to see what kind of '''shape''' the animal was in.''
#: ''We exercise to keep in good physical '''shape'''.''
# The [[appearance]] of something, especially its [[outline]].
#: ''He cut a square '''shape''' out of the cake.''
# A [[figure]] with unspecified appearance; especially a [[geometric]] figure.
#: ''What '''shape''' shall we use for the cookies?  Stars, circles, or diamonds?''
# [[form|Form]]; [[formation]].
#* '''2006''', Berdj Kenadjian, Martin Zakarian, ''From Darkness to Light'':
#*: What if God's plans and actions do mold the '''shape''' of human events?

